      <div class="repair-card">
        <h3>Liebherr CS 1360 counter-depth integrated, Bel Air</h3>
        <p><strong>Symptom:</strong> Owner noticed produce wilting in the BioFresh drawer noticeably faster than it had been. Drawer interior showed condensation buildup on the small inner door panel. Unit was 6 years old.</p>
        <p><strong>Diagnosis:</strong> Classic 2015-2019 CS-series BioFresh humidity sensor failure pattern. Sensor reading out of tolerance on diagnostic meter. Drawer seal and circulation fan checked and found within spec — sensor was the isolated failure.</p>
        <p><strong>Repair:</strong> BioFresh humidity sensor replacement with OEM Liebherr part (in stock on truck). Recalibrated drawer humidity setpoint on the unit's control system. Verified normal humidity hold after 24-hour soak test (owner confirmed by phone next day).</p>
        <p><strong>Cost & time:</strong> $325 total. Same-day, completed on the diagnostic visit in 90 minutes.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="repair-card">
        <h3>Liebherr CBNPgb 5956 freestanding combination, Hancock Park</h3>
        <p><strong>Symptom:</strong> Refrigerator section warming to 45°F overnight; freezer section unaffected, holding -2°F normally. Owner reported the issue started gradually over a week.</p>
        <p><strong>Diagnosis:</strong> DuoCooling refrigerator-side circuit fault — the dual-circuit architecture isolated the failure to the fresh-food side. Evaporator fan in refrigerator compartment failed (motor seized). Compressor and freezer circuit operating normally. Customer asked about parts lead time; we identified the OEM fan motor was 5-day lead through Liebherr USA NJ.</p>
        <p><strong>Repair:</strong> Pre-ordered the fan motor on the diagnostic visit, returned 5 days later, replaced the motor, verified normal fresh-food side cooldown to 38°F within 6 hours. DuoCooling refrigerator side restored to spec.</p>
        <p><strong>Cost & time:</strong> $425 total. Two-visit timing due to parts lead, total 2.5 hours on-site across both visits.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="repair-card">
        <h3>Liebherr WS 17800 wine storage column, Pacific Palisades</h3>
        <p><strong>Symptom:</strong> Lower zone temperature drifting upward, set point 56°F but reading 62°F. Upper zone holding correctly at 48°F. Wine cellar installation, owner concerned about extended exposure for the lower-zone red wine collection.</p>
        <p><strong>Diagnosis:</strong> Lower-zone temperature sensor reading out of spec — sensor itself failed, not the compressor or refrigerant circuit. Upper-zone sensor checked separately and found within tolerance. Replacement sensor required pre-order (10-day lead time).</p>
        <p><strong>Repair:</strong> Customer opted to temporarily relocate the most heat-sensitive bottles to a backup wine fridge during the lead time. Returned 10 days later, replaced lower-zone sensor with OEM Liebherr part, verified both zones holding within spec over 48-hour soak. Customer returned bottles to the column.</p>
        <p><strong>Cost & time:</strong> $385 total. Two-visit timing, 90 minutes on-site total.</p>
      </div>
